Section 1. Problem Domain Description

The gender wage gap or pay gap is the average difference in salary for men and women working for certain companies or in certain industries. Due to a history of patriarchal societies globally where it was forbidden for women to attain certain rights and privileges through a social hierarchy, the effect has left us with a contemporary era where women have attained the right to work and make a living but the inequality is rooted within the amount of money women get paid while doing equal or more work than their other gender counterparts. What is specific to our report is helping the public understand this gap within the technology industry with variables such as location, companies, and education in comparison with average salary data from around the world. This domain is worth analyzing because we are living in a generation where conversations on possible solutions to wage inequalities are being initiated, but literal action has yet to be taken within our governments and societies. Especially in the technological industry, one of the highest paying industries and with the fastest expansion all over the world, equal pay is something that has not been quickly prioritized. In this report, we will explain the urgency that needs to be after the priority of equal pay across genders through understanding the average wages of countries and average wages in the technology industry.

Question 3. Significant Outliers Explanation and Analysis

In our datasets, the significant outliers we had was with our salaries. For both datasets, we had some salaries that were over one million dollars! We noticed that this data skewed our boxplots and decided to wrangle each dataframe to only include salaries that were less than 250,000 dollars. In the above boxplots, you can see how there are still some outliers close to the 250,000 dollar mark. Before eliminating all salaries above 250,000 dollars, there were far more outliers that made the actual box part of the plot nonexistant. Ultimately, choosing to wrangle our dataset made our boxplots actually readable in addition to making our future analysis more accurate. Additionally, for our tech salaries dataset, some of the salaries were not inputted. This was skewing our boxplots to have a minimum value of zero so we decided to wrangle this data set to only include salaries that were great than 10,000 dollars and to not include missing values.

Another thing we experienced was for our tech salaries dataset, there were a lot of different types of education listed. We decided to only use the most common types of education and focus on recieving a High School Diploma, Bachelors Degree, Masters Degree, or Doctorate..

The final thing worth mentioning for our tech salaries dataset was that of the over 4,000 reported salaries, only 167 were reported by females. Not only is this a stark representation of the lack of women in the technology industry, it means that some of our analysis done on women may be inaccurate because of the small amount of data we have to go on. Additionally, wre had some outlier genders and decided to wrangle our dataset to only include people who identified as male or female.

Locksley: Does education level affect the average compensation between different genders?

Question 1. Introduction and Explanation of Question

My question will use the Reddit Tech Salary DataSet. The education level aspect of my dataset is supposed to represent the highest level of education that person recieved. Although there are multiple education levels listed in the dataset, the primary ones I will be focusing are high school diploma, associate degree, bachelors degree, masters degree, and doctorate. For gender, I am only going to focus on people who identify themselves as male or female. Finally, for salary, I am going to focus on the average base salary and not include bonuses, stock options, etc.

Question 2 - Data Analysis Method

My data analysis method involved taking the average salary for men and women of different education levels and comparing them. In order to do this, I first had to create a new dataframe that included the average salary for men and women for a High School Diploma, Bachelors Degree, Masters Degree, and Doctorate. At this point, I created a scatterplot that represented the means for each of these education levels. Although I would have preferred to be more gender neutral, I decided it would be the most intuitive if I made the male averages blue and the female averages red in my scatterplot.

Question 4 - Result Evaluation

Overall, my plot indicates that a higher education results in a higher salary, thje primary exception for this being earning a Masters Degree for men. Unlike women who see an average increase of 256 dollars a year, men are seeing an average decrease of 5,454 dollars for obtaining a Masters degree. This is especially interesting because in a time when undergraduate degrees are worth less, it is fairly common to pursue a Masters Degree. Is it possible that people in the tech industry should not waste time and/or money pursuing a degree that produces a very little increase (or decrease) in their salary?

A second observation I made is that it seems very benefical to pursue a Doctorate. For example, men with a Doctorate earn on average 30,290 dollars more than men with a Bachelors degree and women with a Doctorate earn on average 43,170 dollars more than women with a Bachelors degree. This is especially interesting because it is stereotypically believed that most people with a Doctorate earn less because they are working in Acadamia. I think more research needs to be done with more inputted salaries for people with Doctorates before a conclusion can be drawn.

A final observation I made is men earn more on average who have completed their High School Diploma or Bachelors Degree but women earn more who have completed their Masters or Doctorate Degree. In our data, we see that men who have completed their High School Diploma earn 10,137 dollars more than females and, men who have completed their Bachelors Degree earn on average 3,450 dollars more than Females. However, women who have completed their Masters Degree earn on average 2,260 dollars more than men, and women who have earned their Doctorate earn on average 9,430 dollars more than men. Once again, I think more research needs to be done to include more women in the dataset before a conclusion can be drawn.
